lines.line: > The speaker is introduced as Robert Vey, a George Mason University alum and current archivist. The interview is conducted by Emily Curlee for the university's Oral History Program. Vey discusses his upbringing in Prince William County, Virginia, his education at Bishop Ireton Catholic High School and Woodbridge Senior High School, and his decision to attend George Mason University, where he initially planned to major in physical education.

metadata.title: Introduction and Background
metadata.synopsis: The speaker is introduced as Robert Vey, a George Mason University alum and current archivist. The interview is conducted by Emily Curlee for the university's Oral History Program. Vey discusses his upbringing in Prince William County, Virginia, his education at Bishop Ireton Catholic High School and Woodbridge Senior High School, and his decision to attend George Mason University, where he initially planned to major in physical education.

lines.line: > The speaker started at Mason in 1985 as a freshman. He describes his initial impressions of the university, including the cost of tuition and parking, and his feelings of disconnection from campus life as a commuter student. Despite his good academic performance, he felt somewhat indifferent about the college experience at that time.

metadata.title: College Experience at Mason

lines.line: > The speaker recalls various features of the Mason campus during his time as a student, such as the layout of buildings and the presence of temporary structures like the Humanities module. He also mentions the lack of certain facilities that are present today and describes the general atmosphere and physical changes on campus over the years.

metadata.title: Campus Changes and Memories
metadata.synopsis: The speaker recalls various features of the Mason campus during his time as a student, such as the layout of buildings and the presence of temporary structures like the Humanities module. He also mentions the lack of certain facilities that are present today and describes the general atmosphere and physical changes on campus over the years.

lines.line: > The speaker discusses his limited engagement with Mason sports, particularly remembering the achievements of the women's soccer team and the men's basketball team during his time. He also recalls significant events on campus, such as concerts, the opening of the Patriot Center, and the impact of the space shuttle disaster on the student body.

metadata.title: Mason Sports and Events

lines.line: > After an uninspiring start to his college career, the speaker left Mason to work but eventually returned to complete a degree in American Studies. He then worked at the National Archives before returning to Mason as an employee. He discusses influential professors and how they impacted his educational and career trajectory.

metadata.title: Transition from Student to Employee
metadata.synopsis: After an uninspiring start to his college career, the speaker left Mason to work but eventually returned to complete a degree in American Studies. He then worked at the National Archives before returning to Mason as an employee. He discusses influential professors and how they impacted his educational and career trajectory.

lines.line: # Working at Mason and University Growth

> The speaker describes his return to Mason as an employee and the changes he observed. He discusses the construction of new facilities like the Johnson Center and the Krasnow Institute, and the development of the Prince William campus. He also reflects on the failed initiative to start a football program and the decision to focus on basketball.

lines.line: > The speaker reflects on the transformation of Mason from a largely commuter school to a vibrant university community. He notes the increased school spirit, the impact of the Office of University Life, and the growth in athletics and student engagement. He expresses pride in the university's development and his role in its history.
